{
  "doc_id": "20866",
  "text": "Our previous studies of stoned mutants documented severely impaired synaptic transmission and a reduced number of morphologically abnormal SVs, suggesting a defect in vesicular recycling at the synapse [CITATION_1] . To assay for SV recycling defects directly, we used the fluorescent lipophilic dye FM1-43 in membrane retrieval and SV-recycling assays at the NMJ. Extracellularly applied FM1-43 dye is incorporated into SVs after endocytosis, reliably maintained in SVs and vesicular intermediates, and released during stimulated exocytosis [CITATION_2] . Incubating Drosophila larval NMJ preparations with FM1-43 in a depolarizing solution of high K ϩ (90 mM) results in specific dye incorporation in SVs of the presynaptic boutons that can be released after subsequent depolarization and fusion [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . We used this analysis, in various experimental paradigms, to assay endocytosis and SV recycling in stoned mutant NMJs.",
